# Accessibility Writing Guidelines

## 1. Plain language

Plain language is not simplification — it's precision. The goal is to remove the cognitive overhead of decoding your sentences so readers can focus on understanding the content.

### Write short sentences

Aim for sentences under 25 words. If a sentence needs more, look for a natural break.

| Long | Shorter |
|---|---|
| In the event that you have not yet configured your environment, you will need to complete the setup process before proceeding to the next step. | Before you continue, complete the environment setup. |

### Use common words

Choose the shorter, more common word when you have options. Technical terms are fine — jargon is not.

| Avoid | Prefer |
|---|---|
| utilize | use |
| leverage | use |
| facilitate | help, make, allow |
| in order to | to |
| at this point in time | now |
| prior to | before |

### Define technical terms on first use

When a term is necessary (and many technical terms are), define it the first time you use it. After that, use the term without re-explaining.

> The SDK (software development kit) includes libraries, code samples, and documentation. To install the SDK, run...

### Avoid idioms and figurative language

Idioms don't translate well — across languages or across contexts. "Under the hood," "out of the box," and "hit the ground running" may be opaque to non-native English speakers and some neurodivergent readers.

Say what you mean directly.

