## 2. Structure and navigation

Readers with cognitive disabilities, attention differences, or reading difficulties rely heavily on structure to navigate. Good structure also reduces cognitive load for everyone.

### Use headings as a skeleton

Every page should have a logical heading hierarchy that makes sense when read in sequence — because that's how screen readers and keyboard users often navigate.

- One H1 per page (the page title)
- H2 for major sections
- H3 for sub-sections within an H2
- Never skip a level (H1 → H3 with no H2 in between)

Headings are labels, not prose. Write them to be understood out of context:

| Vague | Descriptive |
|---|---|
| More about this | Authentication options |
| Next steps | How to test your integration |

### Write descriptive link text

Screen readers often pull up a list of all links on a page. Link text must make sense in isolation.

| Inaccessible | Accessible |
|---|---|
| Click [here] for the API reference | See the [API reference] |
| [Read more] about authentication | [Authentication overview] |
| The full guide is [available here] | See the [full integration guide] |

### Use lists for enumerable items

If you're listing three or more things, use a list — not a comma-separated sentence. Lists are easier to scan and easier to navigate with assistive technology.

### Table of contents for long pages

For any page longer than 3–4 sections, include a table of contents at the top. This allows readers to jump directly to what they need without scrolling.

