## 3. Images and visual content

### Write meaningful alt text

Alt text is read aloud by screen readers and displayed when images don't load. It should describe what the image *shows*, not what it *is*.

**Formula:** `[Type of image] showing [what it depicts, specifically]`

```markdown
<!-- Good -->
![A sequence diagram showing the three-step OAuth 2.0 flow: client requests token, server validates credentials, server returns access token](oauth-flow.png)

<!-- Not enough -->
![OAuth flow](oauth-flow.png)

<!-- Redundant -->
![Image of a diagram of the OAuth flow](oauth-flow.png)
```

For decorative images that add no information, use empty alt text (`alt=""`). This tells screen readers to skip the image.

### Include text alternatives for complex visuals

If a diagram is the only way to understand a concept, readers who can't see the diagram are blocked. For complex visuals (architecture diagrams, multi-step flows, comparison charts), include a text description:

> The diagram above shows the three-layer architecture: the client layer sends requests to the API gateway, which routes them to either the auth service or the data service depending on the request type.

### Don't use color as the only signal

If your diagram uses color to show status (red = error, green = success), also use shape, label, or pattern. Color-blind readers, and readers printing in grayscale, need the information to be available another way.

