## 4. Code and technical content

### Don't rely on syntax highlighting alone

Code examples should be readable even without color. Use comments in code to label important sections:

```python
# Authenticate and get a session token
token = client.authenticate(api_key=API_KEY)

# Use the token to make a request
response = client.get("/data", headers={"Authorization": f"Bearer {token}"})
```

### Label code block languages

Always specify the language on fenced code blocks. This enables syntax highlighting, which helps readers parse structure — and also tells assistive technology what kind of content it is.

### Provide plain-language context before code

Don't drop a code block without explaining what it does. A reader using a screen reader will hear the code read character by character unless they skip it — they need the surrounding prose to tell them whether the block is worth reading.

> The following example shows how to initialize the client with a custom timeout. Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual key.

```python
client = APIClient(api_key="YOUR_API_KEY", timeout=30)
```

